To take an example of perhaps the greatest de- gree of mental deprivation resulting from these causes, we will consider the case of the ‘⁶ well-to- do” yeoman. He leaves school, say at fourteen or fifteen. Rating his stock of knowledge at its highest probable measure, we may fairly presume that he has not travelled further along the road of learning, than to have come within easy distance of the fair domain of letters. Having got so far, the generality of men turn back. Of course he must, under any circumstances, spend most of his time in at least directing the course of out-door labour. We are not about to recommend seden- tary habits to the farmer3 but what we design to show is, that the intelligent boy of fifteen ought not, as a matter of course, to content himself with the fruitless fact of just so much book-learning, just so much classical or scientific learning even, as he may have acquired during his six or seven years at the grammar-school—as if that, indeed, were but dead weight, cumbering his hrain, and with which, in fact, it had better never have been freighted: but that he ought to regard these acr quirements as so much seed sown in faith of a coming harvest—as so much virgin ore, wherewith to compare the metal that may be given him for gold, when he can no longer refer it to the judg- ment of the assayer.
